Page 16

Figure 1. Gradient-echo sequences generally consist of repeated RF pulses with a spacing TR, and imaging gradients. The RF flip angle (α) is usually constant, while the phase angle (φ) can be constant, or can increment linearly or quadratically with the repetition number. At the end of the repetition, the sequence may have balanced gradients, spoiler gradients, or RF spoiling, leading to preservation, averaging, or elimination of remaining signal, and very different image contrast and properties. The choice of flip angle also alters contrast, while repetition time (TR) and echo time (TE) are often minimized subject to other constraints, except when generation of T2* contrast is desired.

