Figure 3. In balanced steady-state free precession, magnetization precesses around the Mz axis along the surface of an ellipsoid by some angle ψ, between planes separated by the flip angle, α as viewed along each axis (a,b,c). The precession angle ψ depends on resonant frequency as well as gradient-induced precession. Together, angles ψ and α determine the Mz (longitudinal) and Mxy (signal) components and the “effective” flip angle β (a). The resulting signal vs precession (ψ) plot (d) highlights the same precession angles ψ of interest including no precession (blue), maximum signal (pink), different precession directions (yellow), precession over 180° (dotted pink, red), and signal nulls when β=180° (green). These same angles are shown in (c), with squares and diamonds marking the position immediately after and before an RF pulse. Arrowheads in (c) mark magnetization midway through TR, which is aligned along the positive and negative Mx-axis depending on amount of precession. (As described in the Appendix, the equatorial radius of the ellipse is
, which is the basis of T2/T1 contrast in gradient-echo sequences).
J Magn Reson Imaging. Author manuscript; available in PMC 2013 December 01.

Hargreaves

Page 19

Figure 4.
Balanced SSFP transverse magnetization distribution at different time points. Depending on precession angle ψ, the transverse components begin distributed along an ellipse, are
refocused along ±Mx midway between RF pulses, and end again on an ellipse, with each spin reflected about the Mx axis from the starting point. At all points the phase is linear with ψ, and has discontinuities of π at ψ=(2n+1)π, where n is an integer. (These assume
alternating RF sign, though similar principles apply for different RF phase increments.)

